<http://dx.doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3629.1.1>
    bibo:endPage "106" ;
    bibo:issue "1" ;
    bibo:journal "Zootaxa" ;
    bibo:pubDate "2013-03-18" ;
    bibo:startPage "1" ;
    bibo:volume "3629" ;
    dc:creator "Blank, Stephan M.; Shinohara, Akihiko; Altenhofer, Ewald" ;
    dc:date "2013" ;
    dc:title "<strong> The Eurasian species of <em> Xyela </ em> (Hymenoptera, Xyelidae): taxonomy, host plants and distribution </ strong>" ;
    fabio:hasPart <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261372>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261380>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261390>, <http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261360> ;
    a fabio:JournalArticle .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261372>
    dc:description "FIGURES 42–65. Color pattern of head of Xyela species: X. curva group, X. rasnitsyni group, X. julii group (part). Legend: HT—holotype; NT—neotype; PT—paratype." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/5261372/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261380>
    dc:description "FIGURES 105–120. Ovipositor sheaths of Xyela species. All figures at same scale. Legend: HT—holotype; NT—neotype; PT—paratype." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/5261380/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261390>
    dc:description "FIGURES 146–156. Penis valves of Xyela species (X. julii group, part), and male external copulatory apparatus of Xyela in ventral and lateral view. 153–154, X. longula (penis valves removed). 155–156, X. curva (penis valves and volsellae removed). Legend: bpa—basiparamere, br—basal ring, gon—gonomacula, har—harpe, lap—lateral apodeme, vol—volsella. Figs 147, 150 and 152 reproduced from Blank et al. (2005)." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/5261390/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

<http://dx.doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5261360>
    dc:description "FIGURE 19. Records of three West Palearctic, subalpine Xyela species, X. helvetica (2 specimens from 2 collection sites), X. obscura (221 specimens from 30 collection sites) and X. uncinatae (48 specimens from 9 collection sites) and natural distribution of the (supposed) host plants, Pinus mugo (solid line) and P. uncinata (dashed line, distribution of both pines according to Meusel et al. 1965). The distribution ranges of these pine species overlap in the Alps (see text). Additional literature record included for X. obscura from the Ukraine (Zombori & Ermolenko 1999)." ;
    fabio:hasRepresentation "https://zenodo.org/record/5261360/files/figure.png" ;
    a fabio:Figure .

